revisions.rev:
'''Untouchability''' refers to the social practice of ostracizing a (usually) minority endogamous group by regarding them as "ritually polluted" and segregating them from the mainstream by social custom or legal mandate. Prominent examples of this practice include the ostracization of the [[Dalit]]s and "Arzal" [[caste]]s in [[India]], [[Pakistan]], and [[Bangladesh]], the practice of [[Apartheid]] in [[South Africa]] , the segregation and discrimination of the [[Caste#Yemen caste system|al-Akdham]] in [[Yemen]], and the [[Japan|Japanese]] [[Burakumin]] undercastes.
